Examining the Relationship Between Demographics, Admission Types, and Clinical Outcomes in New York Inpatients (Niagara County)

1. Introduction

Due: October 22nd (Wednesday, End of Day)

This R Markdown performs an exploratory data analysis (EDA) for the dataset Hospital_Inpatient_Discharges.csv. It contains code, explanation, dataset summary, descriptive statistics, graphical displays, variance/SD measures, normality checks, and initial statistical tests.

Welch Two Sample t-test:

Welch Two Sample t-test

data: Length.of.Stay by Age.Group t = -2.0141, df = 5976.3, p-value = 0.978 alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group 30 to 49 and group 70 or Older is greater than 0 95 percent confidence interval: -0.4787434 Inf sample estimates: mean in group 30 to 49 mean in group 70 or Older 5.284008 5.547521

If p-value < 0.05 Since the p-value is less than 0.05, we reject the null hypothesis. This means there is a statistically significant difference between the two group means. In other words, the observed difference is unlikely to have occurred by random chance.

If p-value ≥ 0.05 Since the p-value is greater than 0.05, we fail to reject the null hypothesis. This indicates there is no statistically significant difference between the group means. The difference observed could be due to random variation.
